{"/service/ndnp/curiv/batch_curiv_archylee_ver01/data/sn82016196/00516992360/1945091301/0225.xml":{"full_text":"THIS IS YOUR EAGLE FEATURE PAGE\nPLAIN TALK\nAmong the many plagues af\nfecting the Negro American is\nthe one involving identity and\nthe proper racial designation.\nThere are some who want to\nbe known as Negroes. And\nthere are others who say they\nare colored. Some prefer the\ndesignation, Afro-American,\nand still others want to be\nknown as Race Men and\nWomen. Most southern whites\nknow what they want to call us\nand abritrarily call all of us\n\u25a0nigger.\u201d\nThey see no reason why it\nshould be something else and\ntake pride in the employment\nof the term, pronouncing it, in\nsome cases, with actual affec\ntion. The adopted manner\nwhich the southern white uses\nthe appellation is also shared\nwith most dominant white\nracial stocks, including the\nBritish, German, Irish, Italian\nand the Dutch. All seem to\nrelish the usage of the term,\n\"nigger,\"\n\"Nigger\u201d is a nasty word. It\nis the root of interracial fric\ntion because of the things it\nimplies. The white man's in\nterpretation runs the gamut in\nhis use of the abhored desig\nnation. Sometimes he wants\nNegroes to feel the full im\npact of uhat he means and\nuses the word in such a man\nner as to convey the idea that\nthe object is low. dirty, degrad\ned. black, evil, etc.\nSometimes he wants it\nknown that when he says \"nig\nger\u201d he means his \"dear old\nmammy\u201d or \u201cold Uncle Tom\u201d\nwho bowed himself to death\nwaiting on his father and\nmother back home on the old\nplantation. Foreigners such as\nthe British, German and Dutch\ncall the brown and dark racial\nstocks \u201cnigger\u201d contemptuous\nly and with the idea of con\nveying racial supremacy, as\ndoes, incidentally, the Ameri\ncan white man. Singled out\nparticularly for identification\nwith \"nieeer\u201d are all African\nA LAYMAN'S\nVIEW\nSince it is just about impos\nsible to exhaust the subject, we\nwish to continue our little dis\ncussion of the propaganda pat\ntern which is designed, and\nnot without success, to assign\nus to the status of a lower\ncaste or second class citizen.\nWe turn now to the propagan\nda lines employed by those\nwho would relegate us to ghet\nto through the medium of re\nstrictive covenants.\nWe recently had the pleasure\nof listening to A. L. Foster,\nveteran Urban League execu\ntive of Chicago. During his\ndiscourse he told of some of\nthe propaganda being used by\nthe Chicago fascists who would\nrestrict just about all of that\ncity from just about everybody\nbut the so-called white protes\ntants.\nLittle was revealed in the\nreported Chicago situation on\nthe restrictive covenant propa\nganda front that has not been\nin operation in this City of the\nAngels unless it be the rigor\nous efforts of official Chicago\ntowards combatting their men\nace and the cooperation which\nChicago churches were said\nto have given the mischief\nmakers.\nIn one of the four day\nmonthly conferences w here five\ncommissions are charged by\nthe Mayor s Interracial* Com-\nDO\u2019s and DONT'S\nThe others at the table are your friends. They'll pass\nthe food to you. Do ask them.\nBy DAN GARDNER\u2014\nstocks of whatever shade rec\nognizable.\nThe word \"nigger\" is also\none which Negroes use in\ncreasingly among themselves.\nHighly educated Negroes of\nculture, position and money\nfind the expression common\nplace in polite conversation\nand seem to get the satisfac\ntion out of using it among\nthemselves or in conversation\nwith Negroes of a lower level\nas a farmer gets out of a chew\nof Brown's Mule or old Aunt\nHannah got out of a good lip\nfull of Garrett's Snuff.\nNegro school kids from the\ntime they learn to talk pick up\nthe word\" \"nigger\u201d and make it\na permanent part of their vo\ncabularies.\nIn fact, a \"nigger\u201d has been\nput unconsciously into our\nthinking and while most Ne\ngroes who use the term do not\nmean to convey the implica\ntions put into it by the white\nman, nevertheless, \"nigger\u201d is\npart and parcel of our racial\nvocabulary, whether we like it\ncalled \"nigger\u201d by a white\nor not.\nAlthough we use the word\nso extensively, we. individually\nand collectively will fight at\nthe drop of a hat if we are\nman, or for that matter, by\na mulatto Negro fair enough\nto pass (if he uses it in the\nmanner of the southern white).\nUnwittingly the white man.\nin establishing the word \"nig\nger\" as international stan\ndard of racial identity for a\nso-called inferior group, has\ncreated a situation in which\ncareers in combatting the\nword have been launched.\nYes, there are hundreds of Ne\ngroes. who whether thev real\nize it or not, have dedicated\ntheir life work to eradicating\nthe word \"nigger\" from the\nvocabularies of the nation.\nMany of our top race rights\norganizations are in reality\nfounded on continual cam\npaigning against the causes of\nBx LEON W. STEWARD\nmission to study such areas as\nschools, police, community or\nganizations. etc., a report was\nmade that in one neighborhood\nwhere Chicago citizens were\nshowing disdain for the wiles\nof the \"covenenters\u201d their\nworkers were called together\nin church buildings and in\nstructed to \u201ctell them: (1) that\nall Negro men are rapists and\nno white woman would be safe\nfrom them if they were permit\nted to live in the neighborhood;\n(2) all Negro women are pros\ntitutes and would attract all\nmanner of men into the neigh\nborhood; (3) Negroes will give\nall-night parties to pay for\ntheir homes and bring more\nNegroes of a rowdy sort into\nthe blocks: (4) Negroes do not\nobject to taverns, which would\nsoon follow them into the\nblocks; 15) Negroes in the\nblock will \"lower the real es\ntate values.\"\nWell, these lines have been\nwhispered even here in Los\nAngeles. Have you not heard\nthem\nLocal fascists have not taken\nover our churches yet, or have\nthey? But we are reminded\nthat one of our present neigh\nbors once informed us, after\nlooking us over for a while,\nthat he did not have the least\nobjection to our living next to\nhim but he did object to the\n\"What's in a\nName?\"\nthe term, \"nigger.\" and its use\nby white people. We have had\nand still have noted orators,\nsocial workers, ministers and\nothers who are on the firing\nline, battling daily against the\nuse of the word \u201cnigger.\u201d yet,\nin private or among them\nselves, one can hear the term\nfreely used.\nAll this brings up the ques\ntion: what actual harm does\nthe word do? Does it black\nthe eye. kick the pants, shoot,\nburn, maim, or blind its ob\njective? Are we reduced in\nstature or changed physically\nwhen called such a name by\na white man and remain as\nwe are when a Negro calls us\nthe same thing?\nThere\u2019s a lot of head-scratch\ning that can be done about\nthis matter. If we solve this\nproblem: what shall we be\ncalled, it seems that the way\nwill be cleared for the greatest\nadvancement era in our his\ntory.\nIt would appear that there\nhas been such wasted time\nspent on figuring out what we\nare why and what we want\nto be called. If half that time\nwere devoted to being practi\ncal, in getting things, saving\nmoney, developing poise, and\nracial cohesiveness, our bat\ntle would have more prospect\nof being won quickly. In other\nwords, the time we spend fight\ning against a word could be\nused constructively for our\nadvancement. They called the\nJew everything throughout the\nhistory of the world, yet he\ncontinued to advance until to\nday where he enjoys interna\ntional power and prestige and\nthus can leisurely take up the\nsquabble about being called\n\"kike\u201d or \"sheeny.\u201d During\nthe days of his pilgrimage\nfrom the Egypt of bondage and\noppression, however, he dis\ncarded things that overbur\ndened his advance and among\nthem were the useless fights\nthat expend necessary energy\nthat could go into something\nelse.\nPatterns of\nPropaganda\nfact that his property dropped\nSISOO in value the day we\nmoved in. In L. A. they have\neven figured out the amount\nof the estimated drop in value.\nNow would it not be just\ndandy if Mayor Bowron would\ngive his so-called Interracial\nCommission a little investigat\ning to do in some of our\nL. A. neighborhoods? He would\nlearn of some \"plain and\nfancy\u201d propaganda being em\nployed to get Los Angeles\n\"safe for the white protes\ntants.\u201d Or can his commis\nsion\u2019s SIB.OOO be counted on to\ndo the real work that Mayor\nKelly is getting done for\n525.000 a vear?\nLetters To\nThe Editor\nTo the Editor:\nOn behalf of the Los An\ngeles branch of the National\nAssociation for the Advance\nment of Colored People I want\nto thank you for the splendid\nand wholehearted cooperation\nyou gave during our 1945\nmembership campaign.\nWe are appreciative of the\nfine spirit evidenced not only\nin giving space to our weekly\nnews releases, but also in en\ndorsinb the campaign in your\neditorial columns and in front\npage streamers.\nWe owe much of the success\nof our campaign to your ef\nforts. We shall look forward\nnext year to a bigger and bet\nter campaign with your con\ntinued cooperation.\nThomas L. Griffith, Jr.\nWarning!\n(Ex-Congressman Arthur\nW. Mitchell closed a speech\nof his on the floor of the\nHouse several years ago with\n14 lines taken from Irene\nWest's poem, titled: \"Let's\nSettle It Right\" contained in\n\"The Twain Shall Meet.\" We\nquote them for our readers):\nOh. White-man. why evade the\nissue?\nYour tin-god cycle's done:\nYou've held it down for cen\nturies\u2014\nYou've had a lot of fun.\nGet ready for the Renaissance\nYour system\u2019s obsolete;\nIt's PROVIDENCE! You're up\nagainst,\nAnd that you cannot beat.\nYou haven't settled anything.\nIn God's beholden sight\u2014\nFor no question is ever settled\nUntil it's settled right!\nAnd so\u2014goes on\u2014the fight!\n\u2014IRENE WEST.\n(These lines went Into the\nCongressional Record. Where\nwas Bilbo that day?)\nRATION STAMPS GOOD\nWhat Service Can Veteran\nExpect From The USES?\nBy: T. Frank Hilborn\n(Manager of the Veterans' Service Division, 11th and\nFlower Streets Office of the United States Employment Service).\nLet\u2019s consider this as a heart to heart talk to you as a Vet\neran from a representative of a part of goxernment which has a\nresponsibility of Service to Veterans and who is sincere in its\nadministration.\nYou. along with millions of other veterans, have been en\ngaged in a fight to preserve the right to pursue \"our way of\nlife.\" You may have been in combat or you may have been\nconsidered more valuable by your government in an activity\nwhich contributed to the support of combat units; the impor\ntant factor is that you were a part of our armed forces, whose\nmain objective is to insure our rights to \"Life, Liberty and the\nPursuit of Happiness.\"\nWhile you were doing your part of this job there has been\n(another battle in progress on the home front\u2014the battle of pro\nduction. While our civil population has not suffered the ravages\nof war that have been the fate of the peoples in European and\nAsiatic nations, our social and economic life has been badly dis\nrupted. Many readjustments are necessary in the reestablish\nment of a normal operation of our civilian economy; not only\nin the distribution of returning veterans, but also of war work\ners added to the labor market as war production tapers off.\nRealizing that you have contributed a portion of your life for\nthe purpose of the protection of your country, government has\nprovided for you certain rights and benefits, through the enact\nment of suitable veteran legislation. Some of these are yours\nwithout restriction: some are contingent upon specific conditions.\nCertain government agencies are set up by law to assure your re\nceiving every consideration in the administration of such legisla\ntion.\nRaymond Krah, acting state manpower director for South\nern California, believes that the most important factor in your\nreturn to civil life, should be the securing of suitable employ\nment, Upon this, depends the future standard of living for you\nand your family.\nThis matter of employment is a subject that might well be\ndeserving of consideration. I assume that you have given the\nmatter a lot of thought. As a Veteran you have by law certain\nand well defined reemployment rights, provided you were em\nployed before entering the Armed Service. In addition, whether\nyou were previously employed or not, there are specialized serv\nices available for you. to assist in your determination of whether\nit is more beneficial for you to continue your education, take vo\ncational or on-the-job training, enter into an appcrnticeship pro\ngram or secure immediate employment.\nTrained employment counselors and advisers are available\nin offices of the United States Employment Service to assist in\nmaking such decisions if your education was interrupted, if you\nhave not been previously employed, or if you wish to change your\noccupation. Inasmuch as it would be inadvisable to enter into\nemployment because of the sympathy of an employer toward vet\nerans (You do not want your job to depend upon his attitude to\nward veterans', you will want to secure a job which will most\nfully utilize your highest skill or most clearly defined poten\ntialities. Your future success in employment will depend upon\nhow valuable you can be to your employer.\nAlthough these counselors and advisers will exhaust every\neffort in helping you to decide the course of action that will\ncontribute most to your future welfare, as will the staff of any\norganization or agency concerned with Service to Veterans; you\nhave the responsibility of following through after arriving at a\ndecision.\nIf you arc able to work you owe it to yourself to get started\nas soon as possible. Delay is dangerous, because the longer you\nput it off, the less inclined you are to settle down, and you might\nbecome allergic to work. Then, too, it may now be possible to\nmake good wages in urgent war production work.\nIf, instead, you desire to avail yourself of educational or\ntraining privileges, don\u2019t delay; now is a good time to take ad\nvantage of these benefits and prepare yourself for a vocation\nwhich will promise reasonable employment security when full\nconversion to civilian production is possible. Ask your counselor\nabout such rights.\nYou also have a responsibility to other veterans. If you agree\nto report to an employer for interview, it is important for you\nand for veterans as a group that you keep the appointment. If\nit is impossible for you to make it. extend the employer the\ncourtesy of notifying him in advance of your inability to appear.\nIt not only reflects the dependability of you as an individual,\nbut that of veterans as a whole. This is important; it may have\na decided effect upon your reputation for being dependable.\nTHE NEGRO IN\nLATIN AMERICA\nWill the new atomic bomb\nbe used by American imperial\nism to blast our villages of Ne\ngro Puerto Ricans or Negro\nHaitians asking that the prom\nises of the late war be re\ndeemed by freedom for all peo\nples?\nWill American imperialism\nuse the greatest scientific\ndiscovery ever made by the\ngenius of man to perpetuate\nthe rule of Wall Street over\nour colored brothers of Latin\nAmerica and the other colo\nnial areas?\nIs the atomic age to be an\nother age of rape and robbery,\nof conquest and chicanery vis\nited upon the colored peoples\nof Panama and Persia, of Cuba\nand China?\nOr will man, like a child fi\nnally grown to the stature of\nmaturity, use the atom\u2014which\ncan be used for life as well as\ndeath\u2014to free those of his\nbrothers whom he has kept in\nbondage?\nI don't know the answer to\nthese questions\u2014for they must\nbe answered by rhe people of\nthe world who are both white\npeople and colored people. But\nI know that the colored people\nof Latin America are demand\ning those answers and will\nhelp us work them out.\nColored Latin Americans, to\nwhom I talked in New York\nrecently, expressed great fear\nthat the atomic bomb might be\nused to crush the emerging\npeoples\u2019 revolution of Puerto\nRico, or the atomic bombing\nplanes might be placed by the\nUnited States at the disposal\nof brutal tyrants like Domi\nnican Dictator Rafael Leonidas\nTrujillo. \"The United States\nTHE DAY IS COMING\nNEW YORK\u2014Should the un\nions modify their seniority\nrules to avert disproportionate\nlayoffs of Negro workers? The\nquestion has been hotly de\nbated by practically every un\nion in which Negro workers\nhave won a wartime beach\nhead. Now events have rele\ngated it to the academic\nsphere.\nThe question arises: What\nis to be the effect of this on\nthe thinking of Negro work\ners? Seeing themselves laid\noff in disproportionate num\nbers, while the union stands\nimpotently by or even coop\nerates with the employer in\ndeciding who is to taste the\nbitter fruit of unemployment,\nwill they grow hostile to un\nionism?\nThis. I think, would be trag\nic for the following reasons:\n1. By drawing away from ttje\nrest of the working class. Ne\ngro workers would not only\nneutralize themselves as a po\ntential and progressive social\nforce, but their action would\nfatedly aggravate racial fric\ntion.\n2. To condemn the present\nunion is one thing. To reject\nunionism is something else\nagain. Just because toadstools\nare poisonous doesn't mean we\nshouldn't eat mushrooms. The\nprimary fault of the present\nunions is not that they dis\ncriminate against Negroes,\novertly or covertly. Their pri\nmary fault is that they uphold\nthe social system which makes\nunemployment u n a v o idable.\nhence also the discrimination\nthat job-competition breeds.\nBut this is not a reason to con\ndemn unionism per se: it is,\nrather, a reason to organize a\nunion which does not accept\nthis war\u2014and poverty \u2014breed-\ning system, indeed, one which\nhas as its overriding purpose a\ncomplete reorganization of so\nciety.\n3. Without unionism the\nworking class cannot consoli\ndate its power. Without, power\nthe working class can neither\nresist the encroachments of the\nexploiting class nor abolish the\nsystem of exploitation. There\nfore. to resist unionism is. in\neffect, to cut off every avenue\nof escape from the conditions\nwhich produce discrimination\nand prejudice.\nThe fate of all who feel the\nlash of race prejudice is in\nseparably bound to that of\nthe working class. Nothing\nthe present unions have done\nor may do should cause Ne\ngro workers to forget this\nfact. What the working class\n\u2014of which the overwhelming\nmajority of Negroes are an\nintegral part\u2014does, or does\nnot do will determine\nwhether the age before us is\nto be blighted with hatred\nand conflict or blessed with\nbrotherhood and peace.\nWe are entering upon one of\nthe profoundest critical periods\nof history. In this period we\nmay expect not only that the\nstruggles between employers\nand employees will grow fierc\ner, but also that the bitter riv-\nBy HAROLD PREECE\nhas supplied puppet dictators\nwith arms beforehand to crush\npopular struggles of their own\npeople.\" my friends argued.\nYou've sent them guns and\ncartridges and even L nited\nStates Marines as they did\nback in 1926 to crush the up\nrising of Nicaragua\u2019s Negroes\nand Indians led by General\nSandino.\"\nI hung my head over my\nglass of wine. What could\nI answer them. What can I\nanswer them now that Presi\ndent Truman has said that\nAmerica and Britain the\ntwo great imperialist powers\ncf the world would keep\nthe secret of the atomic bomb\nbetween themselves!\nAre atomic bombs to be\nrained on San Juan in Puerto\nRico if the people of that\nAmerican-subjected nation de\nmand the right of self-determ\nination for all peoples prom\nised in the Atlantic Charter.\nAre the bombs to destroy\nCalcutta in India if another\nlong-suffering colored oeople\ndemand the right of all peo\nples to live and prosper un\nder governments of their own\nchoosing?\nAre the bombs to be used\nagainst our great ally. Russia,\nwhich has wiped out all racial\ndiscrimination but which now\nis the target of attacks from\nredbaiters who are also black\nbaiters?\nI am glad to see Japanese\nimperialism destroyed. It was\na cancer on the world. It had\nto be removed by a surgery\nwhich amounted to warfare.\nBut I doubt very much if we\nwon a victory in the eyes of\nthe world's colored majority\nBy ERIC HASS\nStereotypes in\nEntertainment\nContinued from Page S)\nhow it happened that he not\nonly couldn't get along with\nSouthern whites, but didn't\nfeel at ease among colored peo\nple and couldn't even get along\nwith the members of his own\nfamily.\nOn May 13th of this year,\nan editorial writer on the New\nYork Times came forth with\nthis pertinent comment: \"Sup\npose a gifted Negro writer had\nairy between the unions them\nselves will intensify.\nAlready great jurisdiction\nal battles are looming on the\nhorizon. One effect of these\nwill be further to confuse the\nrank and file who are pawns\nin these struggles for power.\nAnother effect, however, and\na salutary cne, will be to\ndemonstrate that the first\nlaw cf these so-called un\nions is disunion. Instead of\na closed fist capable of strik\ning a blow in labor's behalf\nthey are five sore fingers on\na hand, fit only to shoo flies\naway from the face of the\nemploying class.\nFor the Negro worker to\nmaintain his sense of balance,\nand to resist the bitterness too\noften misdirected toward those\nnearest tn him. will require\nmore than we call faith: it will\nrequire an understanding of\nthe historic role of the working\nclass to liberate mankind from\nprejudice-breeding conditions.\nTAN TOPICS\n'7 don't care uhat the sign says. You'd better wilk\nfaster or I'm going tn give you a good spanking.\u201d\nAtom Offers\nSupreme Test\nwhen we dumped bombs on\nthe Japanese colored peoples\nof the Dutch East Indies and\nthe colored peoples of the\nAmerican and British West In\ndies saying, \"Our turn next.''\nI can imagine the big\nplanters of Puerto Rico and\nthe big planters of Java\nchuckling to themselves that\nthey had discovered away of\ncrushing colonial revolts as\neasily as a boy would crush\na worm by dropping a rock\ncn it.\nMoreover. I am deeply\ngrieved that the first use of\nthis epochal discovery\u2014a\ndream in the mind of untold\ngenerations of scientist s\u2014\nshould have been for mass\n^\u2022laughter We have thought\nthat the first use of the atom,\nwhen it was split, would be to\nrevolutionize modern industry\nand make life more comfort\nable for everybody.\nBut it looks like that we\nwere mistaken. For the spokes\nmen of several big concerns\nhave announced that it will\nnot be possible to run a train\non a lump of coal or a car on\na thimbleful of gasoline,\nthrough atom-splitting, for\n\"generations to come.\"\nPersonally I don't believe\nthem. Neither do the colored\npeoples who know that the\natom could bring about a\npeaceful revolution of the\nentire world society if these\ninterests did not intend to\nbottle the discovery up.\nThe atom is now a path to\ndeath. But it can be made a\npath to life \u2014if the people, in\ncluding the colored people, in\nsist that it be used to make\nlife easier instead of death\nquicker.\nNegroes and\nLabor Unions\nsot out to tell the story of his\nown life, and it turned out to\nbe the story of an averagely\nhappy childhood, of home sur\nroundings where affection was\nnot unknown, of cheerful\nschool days culminating in a\ncollege diploma and leading\non to the beginning of a pros\nperous professional career\u2014\nwould a story like that be\nlikely to find itself in the best\nseller lists?\nIf we are due for a change,\nthat's the sort of change I'd\nlike. I'd want, not only to read\nabcut cultured colored people\nwho live in the North and in\nthe South and who don't have\nto clown and to make idiots\nof themselves to keep from be\ning bothered, but I'd want to\nsee such bocks become best\nsellers, without descending to\nthe use of dirty words to do it.\nI'd want the stage, the films\nand radio to folow suit. I'd\nwant Negroes io be presented,\nnot as angels, nor yet as devils,\nbut as people just like other\npeople, with faults and virtues\njust like the faults and virtues\nof everyone else. Not until\nsuch a thing is possible can\ncolored people be completely\nintegrated into American life.\nNot until enough construc\ntive things about Negroes have\nbeen published and performed\nwill the general public be wise\nenough to know that an \"Anna\nLucasta\" or a \"Black Boy\" are\nsingle instances, not the rec\nord of a race. When will this\ncome to pass? We can only\nask with the Psalmist, \"How\nlong, oh Lord, how long?''\nBy CHARLES ALLEN","height":"30780","width":"22248"}}
